<H1 class=3Dentryviewheading>Open XML Resources for Developers</H1>
<DIV class=3Dentryviewheadersub><SPAN class=3Dhiddentext>Published =
</SPAN>31 March=20
08 03:20 PM</DIV>
<P>Like many people, I thought we'd know the official outcome of the DIS =
29500=20
process today, but it looks like we won't hear the official results =
until after=20
ISO has had a chance to run them by the national bodies who participated =
in the=20
review of the specification, which according to <A=20
href=3D"http://ca.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idCAL301991872008033=
1"=20
mce_href=3D"http://ca.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idCAL30199187200=
80331">Reuters</A>=20
will be Wednesday. </P>
<P>While we wait, I've been thinking about how much attention this =
process has=20
been getting, especially in recent months. Back when Ecma submitted the =
ECMA-376=20
standard to ISO at the beginning of 2007 (451 days ago, if my math is =
right), a=20
relatively small number of people were following the discussion around =
document=20
format standards. That group has expanded significantly, and there are =
now many=20
people following the story of Open XML and DIS 29500. </P>
<P>Since some of those people may be developers who didn't see all of =
the Open=20
XML content that has been made available in the past, I decided to pull =
together=20
a list of links to various resources for Open XML developers. The list =
is=20
included below. I'm sure I've left out a few good resources, so please =
let me=20
know in the comments if you know of a useful Open XML developer resource =
that=20
I've not included here. </P>
<H3>The Basics</H3>
<P>A good place to start if you're brand-new to Open XML is the =
collection of <A=20
href=3D"http://www.youtube.com/user/OpenXML"=20
mce_href=3D"http://www.youtube.com/user/OpenXML">Open XML videos</A> on =
YouTube.=20
You can see various implementations in action on various platforms =
(Windows,=20
Linux, iPhone, Treo, etc.), as well as interviews with Open XML =
developers and=20
other information. </P>
<P>When you're ready to dig into the details, start with <A=20
href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa338205.aspx"=20
mce_href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa338205.aspx">Frank=
 Rice's=20
introductory paper</A> available on MSDN, which covers Open XML document =

architecture and also describes many common scenarios for Open XML =
development=20
projects. Another great article on MSDN is <A=20
href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms771890.aspx"=20
mce_href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms771890.aspx">Erika=
 Ehrli's=20
overview of the DOCX format</A>, which goes into more detail on the most =
popular=20
of the three document types. </P>
<P>If you're familiar with document formats in general and want to read =
about=20
how Open XML compares to other formats, or are curious about how Ecma =
TC45 sees=20
the Open XML formats, be sure to read <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ecma-international.org/news/TC45_current_work/OpenXML%=
20White%20Paper.pdf"=20
mce_href=3D"http://www.ecma-international.org/news/TC45_current_work/Open=
XML%20White%20Paper.pdf">Tom=20
Ngo's whitepaper</A>. Tom is the CTO of NextPage and a TC45 member, and =
he was a=20
contributor to the conformance clause of the original Ecma spec and also =

participated in work on multi-part structure and conformance at the BRM =
last=20
month. </P>
<P>The first book on Open XML development was Wouter Van Vugt's "Open =
XML=20
Explained," which is available as a <A=20
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyID=3D6f264d=
0b-23e8-43fe-9f82-9ab627e5eaa3"=20
mce_href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyID=3D6f=
264d0b-23e8-43fe-9f82-9ab627e5eaa3">free=20
download</A> on MSDN. Toshiba's Yoko Girier has a <A=20
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2008/01/08/open-xml-in-japa=
n.aspx"=20
mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2008/01/08/open-xml-in-=
japan.aspx">Japanese=20
book</A> out for Open XML developers as well. Another reference material =
for=20
developers is the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyID=3D134BCB=
91-DD7B-4209-AC94-2699B9366874&amp;displaylang=3Den"=20
mce_href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyID=3D13=
4BCB91-DD7B-4209-AC94-2699B9366874&amp;displaylang=3Den">Open=20
XML Developer Map</A> poster, which provides an overview of the schemas =
and=20
document types. </P>
<P>For a non-technical high-level overview of Open XML's role in the =
industry,=20
Oliver Bell has written a paper entitled <A=20
href=3D"http://openxmlcommunity.org/documents/OpenForBusiness.pdf"=20
mce_href=3D"http://openxmlcommunity.org/documents/OpenForBusiness.pdf">"O=
pen for=20
Business"</A> that covers that perspective well. </P>
<H3>Advanced Content</H3>
<P>For more detailed coverage of the schemas, take a look at the videos =
of the=20
<A href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/office/bb265236.aspx"=20
mce_href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/office/bb265236.aspx">Open =
XML=20
Developer Workshop</A>. These are videos from a 2-day class on Open XML, =
and you=20
can also download <A=20
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/08/10/developer-worksh=
op-content.aspx"=20
mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/08/10/developer-wo=
rkshop-content.aspx">the=20
content of the workshop</A>, including presentations, sample documents, =
and=20
hands-on labs with code samples. </P>
<P>If you've seen me do an Open XML workshop, you know that there are a =
couple=20
of concepts I really like to stress. One is the the value of custom =
schema=20
support for developers who want to create innovative solutions that =
merge the=20
world of documents and the world of data. Custom schema support opens up =
a new=20
world of possibilities for document-based business processes, and Open =
XML=20
allows custom schemas to be used to tag document content, or for =
discrete=20
"custom XML parts" within a document. </P>
<P>Another favorite topic of mine is how to work with OPC (the Open =
Packaging=20
Conventions that form the structural basis of the Open XML formats). To =
ensure=20
reliable interoperability, developers need to write code that properly =
navigates=20
documents by their relationship structure rather than their physical =
structure,=20
and this is an easy detail to overlook when you're getting started with =
Open XML=20
development. </P>
<P>I've blogged about these two topics in the past, so here are links to =
those=20
posts for more information:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/03/26/custom-xml-marku=
p.aspx"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/03/26/custom-xml-m=
arkup.aspx">Custom=20
  XML markup</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/05/19/custom-schemas-r=
evisited.aspx"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/05/19/custom-schem=
as-revisited.aspx">Custom=20
  schemas revisited</A>=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/09/11/open-xml-impleme=
ntation-test-documents.aspx"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2007/09/11/open-xml-imp=
lementation-test-documents.aspx">OPC=20
  implementation test documents</A></LI></UL>
<H3>Open XML Portals</H3>
<P>The following sites offer a rich set of Open XML content for =
developers,=20
implementers, policy makers, and others:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A href=3D"http://www.openxmldeveloper.org/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://www.openxmldeveloper.org">OpenXmlDeveloper.org</A> =
provides=20
  "how-to" information for developers working on many different =
platforms, and=20
  it has a Forums section where you can post questions about Open XML=20
  development topics.=20
  <LI>The <A =
href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/office/bb265236.aspx"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/office/bb265236.aspx">Office=
 Open=20
  XML Formats Resource Center</A> has links to many comprehensive how-to =

  articles on Open XML development in the .NET environment, as well as=20
  whitepapers and other supporting information.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://www.openxmlcommunity.org/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://www.openxmlcommunity.org">OpenXmlCommunity.org</A> =
has=20
  information about Open XML implementations, case studies, IP =
information, and=20
  other non-technical content that may be useful or interesting to Open =
XML=20
  developers.</LI></UL>
<H3>Developer Tools</H3>
<P>Many of the articles I've linked to above and below cover developer =
tools,=20
but here's a concise list of download links for the most popular tools =
for=20
various environments:=20
<UL>
  <LI><B>Packaging API.</B> If you're running Vista you already have the =

  System.OI.Packaging API. If you're running XP, you'll need to install =
the <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=3D10CC34=
0B-F857-4A14-83F5-25634C3BF043&amp;displaylang=3Den"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=3D10=
CC340B-F857-4A14-83F5-25634C3BF043&amp;displaylang=3Den">.NET=20
  Framework 3.0</A> to get it.=20
  <LI><B>Open XML SDK.</B> The SDK for Open XML formats is a =
higher-level API=20
  for working with Open XML in a .NET environment. All the latest =
information=20
  about the SDK can be found in my recent <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2008/03/13/open-xml-sdk-roa=
dmap.aspx"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/dmahugh/archive/2008/03/13/open-xml-sdk=
-roadmap.aspx">blog=20
  post about the SDK roadmap</A>.=20
  <LI>Java developers should take a look at the open-source <B><A=20
  href=3D"http://www.openxml4j.org/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://www.openxml4j.org/">OpenXML4J API</A></B>.=20
  <LI>Another great alternative for Java developers is <B><A=20
  href=3D"http://dev.plutext.org/trac/docx4j">docx4j</A></B>, an =
open-source=20
  library that creates an in-memory representation of the contents of a =
DOCX.=20
  Jason Harrop and others are building a variety of open-source tools =
for Open=20
  XML developers =E2=80=94 see the <A=20
  href=3D"http://dev.plutext.org/projects.html">dev.Plutext.org</A> site =
for all=20
  the details.=20
  <LI>For PHP developers, check out the <B><A=20
  href=3D"http://www.codeplex.com/PHPExcel"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://www.codeplex.com/PHPExcel">PHPExcel API</A></B>, =
which=20
  provides functionality for easily creating Open XML spreadsheets from =
PHP=20
  applications.</LI></UL>
<P>And here are two other tools that many Open XML developers find =
useful:=20
<UL>
  <LI>The <A href=3D"http://www.codeplex.com/PackageExplorer"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://www.codeplex.com/PackageExplorer">Package =
Explorer</A> is a=20
  handy tool for viewing, editing, and validating the contents of Open =
XML=20
  documents.=20
  <LI>Altova's <A =
href=3D"http://www.altova.com/products/xmlspy/xml_editor.html"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://www.altova.com/products/xmlspy/xml_editor.html">XMLSpy=
</A>=20
  supports Open XML, and Altova CEO Alexander Falk's <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.xmlaficionado.com/2008/01/content-reuse-with-open-xml-=
and-xslt.html"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://www.xmlaficionado.com/2008/01/content-reuse-with-open-=
xml-and-xslt.html">blog</A>=20
  is a good place to learn more about it.</LI></UL>
<H3>Developer-Oriented Blogs</H3>
<P>There are many blogs about Open XML now, including several that =
provide=20
useful developer content on a regular basis. Here are a few of my =
favorite Open=20
XML development blogs:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/brian_jones"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/brian_jones">Brian Jones</A> covers =
a variety=20
  of Open XML topics, and is the best source of information on the =
thinking=20
  behind Open XML and how Microsoft sees the future of XML-based =
documents.=20
  Brian is a member of Ecma TC45 as well.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blogs.infosupport.com/wouterv"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blogs.infosupport.com/wouterv">Wouter Van Vugt</A> =
is an=20
  experienced .NET consultant/trainer who has led numerous Open XML =
workshops,=20
  created Package Explorer, and wrote the "Open XML Explained" book =
mentioned=20
  above. He often posts code samples as well, and is a member of the =
technical=20
  committee that evaluated Open XML for the Netherlands.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/default.aspx"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/default.aspx">Jesper Lund Stocholm</A> =
covers=20
  Open XML and ODF development, and is a very active member of the =
Danish=20
  technical committee that evaluated the Open XML spec.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/erikaehrli"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/erikaehrli">Erika Ehrli</A> is the =
driving=20
  force behind most of the Open XML content on MSDN, and she's also a =
regular=20
  blogger who posts code samples and links to other resources for =
developers.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blogs.developpeur.org/neodante/default.aspx"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blogs.developpeur.org/neodante/default.aspx">Julien =

  Chable</A>, the creator of the OPENXML4J API, has a French-language =
blog with=20
  regular posts on Open XML for Java developers as well as .NET =
developers.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/ericwhite/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/ericwhite/">Eric White</A> blogs =
about Open=20
  XML, LINQ to XML, and related topics. He focuses on the future of XML=20
  development for .NET developers, and posts code samples showing how =
the latest=20
  functional programming concepts can be applied to Open XML.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blog.maartenballiauw.be/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blog.maartenballiauw.be/">Maarten Balliauw</A> is =
the creator=20
  of the PHPExcel API, and blogs on a variety of development topis =
including=20
  Open XML. He covers ASP.NET development as well as PHP development.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://james.newtonking.com/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://james.newtonking.com/">James Newton-King</A> is =
another=20
  blogger who covers a wide range of development topics. His posts on =
Open XML=20
  and LINQ to XML are excellent.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://www.oreillynet.com/pub/au/1712"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://www.oreillynet.com/pub/au/1712">Rick Jelliffe</A> =
blogs about=20
  markup languages and related topics, and has been a major contributor =
to the=20
  debate around Open XML.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/default.asp"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/default.asp">Dennis Hamilton</A> =
has a=20
  lifetime of experience in technology standards, and often writes posts =
that=20
  look beyond the present into the world of possibilities that XML-based =

  document formats present for developers.=20
  <LI><A href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/mordonez/"=20
  mce_href=3D"http://blogs.msdn.com/mordonez/">Mauricio Ordonez</A> =
blogs about=20
  Office development topics, including Open XML, and I'm looking forward =
to some=20
  interesting content he'll have soon for Open XML developers.=20
  <LI>Finally, this one isn't really a blog, but the <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://forums.microsoft.com/MSDN/ShowForum.aspx?ForumID=3D1647&am=
p;SiteID=3D1"=20
  =
mce_href=3D"http://forums.microsoft.com/MSDN/ShowForum.aspx?ForumID=3D164=
7&amp;SiteID=3D1">Open=20
  XML SDK forum</A> on MSDN is another great place to read developers'=20
  conversations about Open XML development or get your questions=20
answered.</LI></UL>
