  <A id=3Dctl00___ctl00___ctl01___Comments___Comments_ctl11_NameLink=20
  title=3D"James Plamondon">James Plamondon</A> said on April 1, 2008 =
8:57 PM:=20
  </DT>
  <DD class=3D"">
  <P>Our mission is to establish Microsoft's platforms as the de facto =
standards=20
  throughout the computer industry.... Working behind the scenes to =
orchestrate=20
  "independent" praise of our technology, and damnation of the enemy's, =
is a key=20
  evangelism function during the Slog. "Independent" analyst's report =
should be=20
  issued, praising your technology and damning the competitors (or =
ignoring=20
  them). "Independent" consultants should write columns and articles, =
give=20
  conference presentations and moderate stacked panels, all on our =
behalf (and=20
  setting them up as experts in the new technology, available for just=20
  $200/hour). "Independent" academic sources should be cultivated and =
quoted=20
  (and research money granted). "Independent" courseware providers =
should start=20
  profiting from their early involvement in our technology. Every =
possible=20
  source of leverage should be sought and turned to our advantage.</P>
  <P>I have mentioned before the "stacked panel". Panel discussions =
naturally=20
  favor alliances of relatively weak partners - our usual opposition. =
For=20
  example, an "unbiased" panel on OLE vs. OpenDoc would contain =
representatives=20
  of the backers of OLE (Microsoft) and the backers of OpenDoc (Apple, =
IBM,=20
  Novell, WordPerfect, OMG, etc.). Thus we find ourselves outnumbered in =
almost=20
  every "naturally occurring" panel debate.</P>
  <P>A stacked panel, on the other hand, is like a stacked deck: it is =
packed=20
  with people who, on the face of things, should be neutral, but who are =
in fact=20
  strong supporters of our technology. The key to stacking a panel is =
being able=20
  to choose the moderator. Most conference organizers allow the =
moderator to=20
  select the panel, so if you can pick the moderator, you win. Since you =
can't=20
  expect representatives of our competitors to speak on your behalf, you =
have to=20
  get the moderator to agree to having only "independent ISVs" on the =
panel. No=20
  one from Microsoft or any other formal backer of the competing =
technologies=20
  would be allowed =E2=80=93 just ISVs who have to use this stuff in the =
"real world."=20
  Sounds marvelously independent doesn't it? In fact, it allows us to =
stack the=20
  panel with ISVs that back our cause. Thus, the "independent" panel =
ends up=20
  telling the audience that our technology beats the others hands down. =
Get the=20
  press to cover this panel, and you've got a major win on your =
hands.</P>
  <P>Finding a moderator is key to setting up a stacked panel. The best =
sources=20
  of pliable moderators are:</P>
  <P>&nbsp; &nbsp;-- Analysts: Analysts sell out - that's their business =
model.=20
  But they are very concerned that they never look like they are selling =
out, so=20
  that makes them very prickly to work with.</P>
  <P>&nbsp; &nbsp;-- Consultants: These guys are your best bets as =
moderators.=20
  Get a well-known consultant on your side early, but don't let him =
publish=20
  anything blatantly pro-Microsoft. Then, get him to propose himself to =
the=20
  conference organizers as a moderator, whenever a panel opportunity =
comes up.=20
  Since he's well- known, but apparently independent, he'll be accepted =
=E2=80=93 one=20
  less thing for the constantly-overworked conference organizer to worry =
about,=20
  right?</P>
